
[1]swale

   SWALE, n. [probably from vale.] A local word in New England, signifying
   an interval or vale; a tract of low land.

   1. In England, a shade.

                     SWALE, v.i. To waste. [See Sweal.]

    SWALE, v.t. To dress a hog for bacon, by singeing or burning off his
                               hair. [Local.]
